🚁 Tiny Object Detection in Aerial Images
📌 Abstract

Detecting small-scale objects in aerial imagery remains a challenging problem in Computer Vision due to scale variation, low resolution, and dense object distributions. This project investigates the effectiveness of scale-aware inference techniques, specifically image tiling, in improving the detection performance of deep learning models.

We implement a YOLOv8-based detection pipeline and analyze how tiling impacts the model’s ability to detect tiny objects in aerial datasets.

🔍 Problem Statement

Object detection models often underperform on aerial imagery because:

Objects occupy very few pixels
Scene complexity is significantly higher than standard datasets
Models are biased toward larger object scales

This leads to:

Low recall for small objects
Missed detections in dense regions
🎯 Research Objective

This work aims to:

Evaluate the limitations of standard object detection models on small objects
Investigate image tiling as a scale-aware enhancement technique
Quantitatively and qualitatively compare detection performance
Analyze improvements in detecting small objects
🧠 Methodology
Dataset
VisDrone Dataset (benchmark dataset for aerial object detection)
Model
YOLOv8 (Ultralytics)
Selected for its balance between speed and accuracy in real-time detection tasks.
Experimental Setup

Two inference strategies were evaluated:

Baseline Approach
Direct inference on full-resolution images
Tiling-Based Approach
Images divided into smaller patches
Detection performed on each patch
Results aggregated to form final predictions
🔬 Experiments & Analysis
Key Observation
Approach	Result
Baseline YOLOv8	Fails to detect several small objects
Tiling-based Inference	Improved detection and higher object recall
Insight
Tiling increases the effective resolution of small objects
Helps the model focus on localized regions
Reduces the impact of scale imbalance
📊 Evaluation
Qualitative comparison of detection outputs
Observed improvement in:
Number of detected objects
Detection consistency in dense regions

(Note: Quantitative metrics such as mAP can be extended for deeper evaluation.)

🚀 Implementation
Model: YOLOv8 (PyTorch-based)
Interface: Gradio-based web UI
Deployment: Hugging Face Spaces
🌐 Live Demo

👉 https://huggingface.co/spaces/Deepthi2005/TinyObjectDetection

📈 Future Work
Incorporate SAHI (Slicing Aided Hyper Inference) for optimized tiling
Perform quantitative evaluation using mAP, Precision, Recall
Compare with alternative architectures (DETR, Faster R-CNN)
Explore super-resolution techniques for preprocessing
Optimize inference for real-time deployment
📚 Conclusion

This study demonstrates that scale-aware techniques such as image tiling can significantly improve small object detection in aerial imagery. The findings highlight the importance of adapting inference strategies to address scale-related challenges in Computer Vision tasks.
